  <p:title>Entities</p:title>
  <p:slide xml:id="comp-entities">
    <p:title>Entities</p:title>
    <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">There are several sorts of entity. The most common are character entities.</p>
    <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Character entities are normally used when:</p>
    <ul xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      <li>You can't type the character with your keyboard</li>
      <li>The character can't be expressed in the encoding*</li>
      <li>XML requires that you use it</li>
    </ul>
    <h4 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">General Form(s)</h4>
    <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">There are three ways to write an entity:</p>
    <ul xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      <li>Text entities — &amp;lt; = &lt;</li>
      <li>Decimal entities — &amp;#169; = ©</li>
      <li>Hexadecimal entities - &amp;#xA9; = ©</li>
    </ul>
  </p:slide>
  
  <p:slide xml:id="d1e67">
    <p:title>Aside: Hexadecimal</p:title>
    <ul xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      <li>Hexadecimal is base 16</li>
      <li>Used a lot in computer science because it's logically close to binary (base
        2)*</li>
      <li>In hexadecimal, <em>10</em> equals (decimal) <em>16</em></li>
      <li>Because we don't have enough digits, we use <em>A-F</em> to represent
        <em>10-15</em></li>
      <li>So… <ul>
        <li>The copyright (©) symbol is character number 169.</li>
        <li>160 is 10 * 16 so we write that as A0</li>
        <li>9 is just 9 so, adding, we get A9</li>
      </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="footnote">* When you get right down to the smallest details, computers only
      use binary.</p>
  </p:slide>
  
  <p:slide xml:id="d1e116">
    <p:title>Predefined entities</p:title>
    <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">XML defines five entities:</p>
    <table xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      <tr>
        <td>&amp;lt;</td>
        <td>&lt;</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>&amp;gt;</td>
        <td>&gt;</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>&amp;apos;</td>
        <td>'</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>&amp;quot;</td>
        <td>"</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>&amp;amp;</td>
        <td>&amp;</td>
      </tr>
      
    </table>
  </p:slide>
